/* CISA :: content/quiz5.js — CISA Domain 5 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.questions = CISA.questions || [];
CISA.questions.push.apply(CISA.questions, [
{"id":"D5-001","domain":5,"obj":"5A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating an organization's information security program. Which international standard provides the requirements for establishing, implementing, and maintaining an information security management system (ISMS)?","options":["ISO/IEC 9001","ISO/IEC 27002","ISO/IEC 27001","ISO/IEC 20000"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>ISO/IEC 27001</strong> — ISO/IEC 27001 specifies the auditable requirements for an ISMS, against which an organization can be certified; it defines the management-system framework the auditor assesses conformance against.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 9001</b>: is a quality management standard unrelated to security control requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27002</b>: is a code of practice offering control guidance, not certifiable ISMS requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 20000</b>: addresses IT service management, not information security management systems.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-002","domain":5,"obj":"5A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a security architecture that layers perimeter firewalls, network segmentation, host hardening, and application controls. Which security principle does this design BEST demonstrate?","options":["Fail-safe defaults","Least privilege","Defense in depth","Separation of duties"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Defense in depth</strong> — Defense in depth places multiple independent, overlapping control layers so that failure of any single control does not compromise the asset; the layered firewalls, segmentation, hardening, and app controls are the textbook illustration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail-safe defaults</b>: means access is denied unless explicitly granted, not the stacking of protective layers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: restricts each subject to the minimum rights needed and is not what multiple layers illustrate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: splits a task among people to prevent fraud, not a technical layering concept.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-003","domain":5,"obj":"5A1","diff":"medium","q":"When assessing whether information security policies are effective, an IS auditor should FIRST determine that the policies are:","options":["Reviewed by external auditors","Published on the intranet","Written by the security team","Approved by senior management and aligned with business objectives"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Approved by senior management and aligned with business objectives</strong> — Senior-management approval and alignment with business objectives give policy its authority and relevance; without that mandate a policy cannot be enforced, so the auditor confirms this first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reviewed by external auditors</b>: external review is not a prerequisite for policy validity or effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Published on the intranet</b>: publication aids awareness but is meaningless without management approval behind it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Written by the security team</b>: authorship does not confer organizational authority or business alignment.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-004","domain":5,"obj":"5A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is mapping an organization's controls to the NIST Cybersecurity Framework. The five core functions of the framework are Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and:","options":["Remediate","Review","Report","Recover"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Recover</strong> — The NIST CSF core comprises Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover; Recover addresses restoring capabilities and services after a cybersecurity event.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Remediate</b>: describes an activity but is not a named CSF core function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Review</b>: is not part of the CSF function set.</span><span class='qd'><b>Report</b>: is not one of the five NIST CSF core functions.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-005","domain":5,"obj":"5A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor evaluating data classification wants to confirm the organization protects the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of information. These three properties are collectively known as the:","options":["Parkerian hexad","Zero trust model","AAA model","CIA triad"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>CIA triad</strong> — Confidentiality, integrity, and availability form the CIA triad, the foundational model for information security objectives the auditor uses as a control baseline.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Parkerian hexad</b>: is a six-attribute extension, not the classic three-property model named here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Zero trust model</b>: is an architecture philosophy, not the confidentiality-integrity-availability set.</span><span class='qd'><b>AAA model</b>: stands for authentication, authorization, and accounting — an access-control model, not the security objectives.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-006","domain":5,"obj":"5A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notes that an organization has classified all data as 'confidential' regardless of sensitivity. The PRIMARY risk of this over-classification is that it:","options":["Improves data protection uniformly","Wastes resources and dilutes protection of truly sensitive data","Violates ISO 27001 certification","Prevents any data sharing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Wastes resources and dilutes protection of truly sensitive data</strong> — Uniform over-classification applies costly controls to low-value data while diluting focus and resources away from genuinely sensitive assets, undermining the risk-based intent of classification.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Improves data protection uniformly</b>: is a misconception; blanket controls waste effort rather than improving targeted protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Violates ISO 27001 certification</b>: over-classification is inefficient but is not itself a certification violation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Prevents any data sharing</b>: classification governs handling, not an absolute bar on sharing.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-007","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor observes a single door that permits only one person to pass at a time and prevents tailgating into a data center. This control is known as a:","options":["Turnstile bypass","Mantrap","Bollard","Faraday cage"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Mantrap</strong> — A mantrap (access-control vestibule) uses interlocking doors to allow one authenticated person through at a time, directly preventing tailgating/piggybacking into secure areas.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Turnstile bypass</b>: is not a recognized control; a bypass would defeat, not enforce, access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Bollard</b>: is a vehicle barrier, not a personnel anti-tailgating control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Faraday cage</b>: blocks electromagnetic signals, not physical human entry.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-008","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"medium","q":"During a data center walkthrough, an IS auditor wants to verify that a fire-suppression system will not damage electronic equipment when discharged. Which agent is MOST appropriate?","options":["Wet-pipe water sprinklers","A clean agent such as FM-200 or inert gas","Dry chemical powder","Foam suppression"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A clean agent such as FM-200 or inert gas</strong> — Clean gaseous agents (e.g., FM-200, inert gas) suppress fire without leaving residue or conducting electricity, protecting equipment while extinguishing, which is why they are used in data centers.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Wet-pipe water sprinklers</b>: discharge water that damages energized electronics and is unsuitable as the primary equipment-room agent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Dry chemical powder</b>: leaves corrosive residue that harms electronic components.</span><span class='qd'><b>Foam suppression</b>: is conductive and messy, damaging equipment rather than protecting it.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-009","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing environmental controls in a server room. Which control PRIMARILY addresses the risk of equipment overheating?","options":["Heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC)","Water-detection sensors","Biometric door locks","Uninterruptible power supply (UPS)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC)</strong> — HVAC systems maintain temperature and humidity within safe operating ranges, directly mitigating the risk of overheating that degrades or fails equipment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Water-detection sensors</b>: detect leaks and flooding, not heat buildup.</span><span class='qd'><b>Biometric door locks</b>: control physical access and have no role in cooling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Uninterruptible power supply (UPS)</b>: provides short-term power continuity, not temperature control.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-010","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews power-continuity controls. Which device provides immediate battery power to allow systems to shut down gracefully during a short outage?","options":["Uninterruptible power supply (UPS)","Power distribution unit","Surge protector","Diesel generator"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Uninterruptible power supply (UPS)</strong> — A UPS supplies instantaneous battery-backed power during brief outages or the gap before generators start, enabling orderly shutdown and preventing data loss.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Power distribution unit</b>: distributes power but stores none for outage ride-through.</span><span class='qd'><b>Surge protector</b>: absorbs voltage spikes but supplies no backup power.</span><span class='qd'><b>Diesel generator</b>: provides long-term power but takes time to start, leaving an uncovered gap without a UPS.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-011","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds that a data center's CCTV footage is retained for only 24 hours. The PRIMARY concern is that this retention period may:","options":["Be insufficient to investigate incidents discovered after the fact","Overload storage capacity","Improve monitoring quality","Exceed privacy regulations"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Be insufficient to investigate incidents discovered after the fact</strong> — Many incidents are detected days later; a 24-hour retention window means the recorded evidence is already overwritten, defeating the investigative and forensic purpose of the cameras.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Overload storage capacity</b>: short retention reduces, rather than overloads, storage needs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Improve monitoring quality</b>: limited retention weakens, not improves, investigative capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Exceed privacy regulations</b>: a short retention period is more likely to satisfy than exceed privacy limits.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-012","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing visitor management at a secure facility. Which control BEST provides accountability for who was physically present in the building?","options":["Motion-activated lighting","A CCTV camera at the entrance","A signed and time-stamped visitor log with escort assignment","A posted 'authorized personnel only' sign"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A signed and time-stamped visitor log with escort assignment</strong> — A signed, time-stamped visitor log tied to escort assignment creates an auditable record of identity, entry/exit times, and responsibility, providing the accountability the auditor seeks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Motion-activated lighting</b>: is a deterrent/detective aid, not a record of who was present.</span><span class='qd'><b>A CCTV camera at the entrance</b>: records images but does not by itself establish identity or an escort record.</span><span class='qd'><b>A posted 'authorized personnel only' sign</b>: is a deterrent notice that captures no accountability data.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-013","domain":5,"obj":"5A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates the placement of a data center within a corporate building. Which location choice BEST reduces environmental and physical risk?","options":["Basement below ground water level","An interior room on a middle floor away from exterior walls","Adjacent to the loading dock","Top floor near the roof"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An interior room on a middle floor away from exterior walls</strong> — An interior room on a middle floor minimizes exposure to roof leaks, ground flooding, external forced entry, and blast/collision, balancing the competing environmental threats.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Basement below ground water level</b>: raises the risk of flooding and water intrusion.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adjacent to the loading dock</b>: increases physical-access and vehicle-related threats.</span><span class='qd'><b>Top floor near the roof</b>: increases exposure to roof leaks, heat, and lightning.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-014","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is documenting access-control concepts. The process of verifying that a claimed identity is genuine is called:","options":["Accountability","Identification","Authentication","Authorization"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Authentication</strong> — Authentication verifies a claimed identity by validating credentials (something you know/have/are), confirming the subject is who it claims to be before access decisions are made.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Accountability</b>: traces actions to a subject after the fact, not the verification step.</span><span class='qd'><b>Identification</b>: is merely asserting an identity (e.g., a username), not proving it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Authorization</b>: grants permissions after identity is already verified.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-015","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a biometric system and finds the crossover error rate (CER) is high. The CER represents the point where:","options":["The false rejection rate is highest","Enrollment fails","The false acceptance rate is zero","The false acceptance rate equals the false rejection rate"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The false acceptance rate equals the false rejection rate</strong> — The CER (equal error rate) is where FAR equals FRR; a lower CER indicates a more accurate biometric, so a high CER signals poorer overall accuracy the auditor should flag.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The false rejection rate is highest</b>: the crossover is a balance point, not the FRR maximum.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enrollment fails</b>: CER measures matching accuracy, not enrollment failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>The false acceptance rate is zero</b>: FAR is not zero at the crossover; both error rates are equal and nonzero.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-016","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor observes that terminated employees' accounts remained active for weeks. The control that MOST directly addresses this is:","options":["Periodic access recertification","Timely deprovisioning tied to the HR termination process","Password complexity rules","Single sign-on"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Timely deprovisioning tied to the HR termination process</strong> — Deprovisioning integrated with the HR termination workflow ensures access is revoked promptly when employment ends, closing the exact window the auditor observed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Periodic access recertification</b>: catches stale access only at review intervals, not immediately on termination.</span><span class='qd'><b>Password complexity rules</b>: strengthen credentials but do nothing to remove a terminated user's access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Single sign-on</b>: centralizes login but does not by itself trigger timely account removal.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-017","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating an access model where permissions are assigned to job functions rather than to individuals. This model is:","options":["Role-based access control (RBAC)","Mandatory access control (MAC)","Rule-based access control","Discretionary access control (DAC)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Role-based access control (RBAC)</strong> — RBAC assigns permissions to roles that map to job functions and then places users into roles, simplifying administration and supporting least privilege — exactly the description given.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mandatory access control (MAC)</b>: enforces access via security labels/clearances set by the system, not job-function roles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rule-based access control</b>: applies conditions/rules (e.g., time, IP) rather than assigning rights to job roles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discretionary access control (DAC)</b>: lets resource owners grant access at their discretion, not by predefined job roles.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-018","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is verifying multi-factor authentication. Which combination represents TRUE multi-factor authentication?","options":["A password and a hardware token","Two different passwords","A username and a password","A password and a PIN"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A password and a hardware token</strong> — True MFA combines factors from different categories; a password (something you know) plus a hardware token (something you have) uses two distinct factor types.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Two different passwords</b>: remain a single factor type (knowledge), not multi-factor.</span><span class='qd'><b>A username and a password</b>: a username is an identifier, not an authentication factor.</span><span class='qd'><b>A password and a PIN</b>: are both 'something you know', so this is single-factor with two knowledge items.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-019","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is testing the principle that users should have only the access necessary to perform their duties. This principle is:","options":["Defense in depth","Need to know","Separation of duties","Least privilege"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Least privilege</strong> — Least privilege limits each subject's access rights to the minimum required for their tasks, reducing the attack surface and potential damage from misuse.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth</b>: is about layered technical controls, not minimizing user rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Need to know</b>: restricts information access to what's necessary but is narrower than the rights-minimization principle named here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: divides a critical task among multiple people, a distinct anti-fraud principle.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-020","domain":5,"obj":"5A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews privileged-access management. The BEST control to limit the risk of administrators abusing standing access is to:","options":["Share a single admin account","Disable logging on admin actions","Give all admins domain-admin rights","Implement just-in-time access with session recording and approval"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Implement just-in-time access with session recording and approval</strong> — Just-in-time privileged access grants elevated rights only when needed, for a limited time, with approval and session recording, minimizing standing privilege and providing accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Share a single admin account</b>: destroys individual accountability and enables abuse.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable logging on admin actions</b>: removes the audit trail, worsening the risk rather than controlling it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Give all admins domain-admin rights</b>: maximizes standing privilege and violates least privilege.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-021","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing network defenses. A device that inspects traffic and can actively block malicious packets in-line is a(n):","options":["Intrusion prevention system (IPS)","Network tap","Syslog server","Intrusion detection system (IDS)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Intrusion prevention system (IPS)</strong> — An IPS sits in-line and can drop or block malicious traffic in real time, whereas detection-only systems merely alert; the ability to actively block is the distinguishing feature.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Network tap</b>: passively copies traffic for monitoring and cannot block anything.</span><span class='qd'><b>Syslog server</b>: collects log data and takes no blocking action on traffic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Intrusion detection system (IDS)</b>: only detects and alerts; it does not sit in-line to block traffic.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-022","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor examines a firewall that tracks the state of active connections and permits return traffic only for established sessions. This is a:","options":["Stateful inspection firewall","Proxy content filter","Network address translator","Packet-filtering firewall"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Stateful inspection firewall</strong> — A stateful inspection firewall maintains a state table of active connections and allows return traffic that matches established sessions, providing stronger control than stateless filtering.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Proxy content filter</b>: filters application content and does not primarily maintain a connection state table for this purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network address translator</b>: translates addresses and does not itself provide stateful security filtering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Packet-filtering firewall</b>: evaluates packets individually against rules without tracking connection state.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-023","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing remote-access security. Which technology provides an encrypted tunnel for remote users to reach internal resources over the internet?","options":["Domain name system (DNS)","Network time protocol (NTP)","Virtual private network (VPN)","Virtual local area network (VLAN)"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Virtual private network (VPN)</strong> — A VPN establishes an encrypted tunnel (e.g., via IPsec or TLS) across the untrusted internet, protecting the confidentiality and integrity of remote-access traffic.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Domain name system (DNS)</b>: resolves names to addresses and offers no secure tunneling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network time protocol (NTP)</b>: synchronizes clocks and has no remote-access encryption role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Virtual local area network (VLAN)</b>: segments a LAN logically but provides no encryption over the internet.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-024","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing a network architecture that assumes no implicit trust and verifies every request regardless of origin. This approach is BEST described as:","options":["Air-gapped networking","Flat network design","Perimeter-based security","Zero trust architecture"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Zero trust architecture</strong> — Zero trust removes implicit trust based on network location and continuously authenticates and authorizes every request, minimizing lateral movement and insider risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Air-gapped networking</b>: physically isolates a network but is not the continuous-verification model described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Flat network design</b>: lacks segmentation and trust boundaries, increasing rather than removing implicit trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>Perimeter-based security</b>: trusts internal traffic once inside the perimeter — the opposite of zero trust.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-025","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a network zone that hosts public-facing web servers and is isolated from the internal LAN by firewalls. This zone is called a:","options":["Storage area network","Management VLAN","Virtual private network","Demilitarized zone (DMZ)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Demilitarized zone (DMZ)</strong> — A DMZ is a screened subnet positioned between the internet and the internal network to host public-facing services while limiting exposure of internal systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Storage area network</b>: is a dedicated storage network, unrelated to hosting public services.</span><span class='qd'><b>Management VLAN</b>: segregates administrative traffic, not internet-facing public servers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Virtual private network</b>: is an encrypted tunnel technology, not a screened public-server subnet.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-026","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating endpoint protection that continuously monitors devices, detects suspicious behavior, and enables investigation and response. This capability is:","options":["A BIOS password","Endpoint detection and response (EDR)","A screen saver policy","Full-disk defragmentation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Endpoint detection and response (EDR)</strong> — EDR continuously records endpoint activity, detects threats through behavioral analysis, and supports containment and investigation — a modern control beyond signature antivirus.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A BIOS password</b>: restricts firmware access but does not monitor or respond to threats.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen saver policy</b>: locks idle screens but provides no threat detection or response.</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk defragmentation</b>: is a performance-maintenance task with no security function.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-027","domain":5,"obj":"5A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews a control that authenticates and checks the security posture of devices before allowing them onto the network. This control is:","options":["A jump host","Network access control (NAC)","A load balancer","A reverse proxy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Network access control (NAC)</strong> — NAC evaluates device identity and compliance (patch level, AV status) before granting network access, enforcing posture requirements at connection time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A jump host</b>: is a hardened intermediary for administration, not a network-admission posture control.</span><span class='qd'><b>A load balancer</b>: distributes traffic across servers and performs no posture assessment.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reverse proxy</b>: fronts servers to filter inbound requests but does not gate device admission by posture.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-028","domain":5,"obj":"5A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating controls that detect and block sensitive data from leaving the organization via email or uploads. This technology is:","options":["Disk defragmentation","Data warehousing","Data loss prevention (DLP)","Data deduplication"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong> — DLP inspects data in use, in motion, and at rest, and enforces policies to detect and block exfiltration of sensitive information such as PII or intellectual property.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disk defragmentation</b>: reorganizes disk storage for performance, not data protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data warehousing</b>: consolidates data for analytics and does not block leakage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data deduplication</b>: eliminates redundant storage blocks and has no exfiltration-prevention role.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-029","domain":5,"obj":"5A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a DLP deployment. For DLP to accurately identify what to protect, the organization MUST first have:","options":["A next-generation firewall","Accurate data classification and identification","A SIEM platform","Full-disk encryption"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Accurate data classification and identification</strong> — DLP relies on knowing which data is sensitive; without accurate data classification and identification, DLP rules cannot correctly match and protect the right content.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A next-generation firewall</b>: controls network traffic but does not tell DLP which data is sensitive.</span><span class='qd'><b>A SIEM platform</b>: aggregates logs and does not define sensitive-data categories for DLP.</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: protects data at rest on lost devices but does not classify content for DLP matching.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-030","domain":5,"obj":"5A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds DLP is configured only for outbound email. The MOST significant gap this leaves is that sensitive data could still leave via:","options":["Cloud uploads and removable media","Internal email only","Print jobs to a shredder","Encrypted backups"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Cloud uploads and removable media</strong> — Email-only DLP ignores other egress channels; sensitive data can exfiltrate through cloud storage uploads and USB/removable media, which the auditor should flag as uncovered.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Internal email only</b>: internal mail stays inside the organization and is not the primary leakage concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Print jobs to a shredder</b>: describe destruction of output, not an exfiltration path.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypted backups</b>: are a protection mechanism, not a typical uncontrolled exfiltration channel.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-031","domain":5,"obj":"5A5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates DLP effectiveness and finds it generates many false positives that block legitimate business email. The PRIMARY risk of unaddressed false positives is that:","options":["Users will seek workarounds that bypass the control","Storage costs will rise","Firewalls will fail open","Encryption keys will be exposed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Users will seek workarounds that bypass the control</strong> — Excessive false positives frustrate users, who then adopt unsanctioned channels to get work done, undermining the very control and creating unmonitored data flows.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Storage costs will rise</b>: false positives affect blocking decisions, not storage consumption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Firewalls will fail open</b>: DLP tuning does not determine firewall failure behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption keys will be exposed</b>: false positives relate to content matching, not key management.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-032","domain":5,"obj":"5A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor classifies DLP coverage by state of data. Monitoring files being copied to a USB drive addresses data:","options":["In use","In transit","In escrow","At rest"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>In use</strong> — Data in use is data actively being accessed or manipulated at an endpoint; copying to USB is an endpoint action, so endpoint DLP controlling that copy protects data in use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>In transit</b>: refers to data moving across a network, not an endpoint copy operation.</span><span class='qd'><b>In escrow</b>: is not a data state; escrow concerns holding keys or assets.</span><span class='qd'><b>At rest</b>: refers to stored data not currently being accessed or moved.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-033","domain":5,"obj":"5A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing controls to prevent intellectual property theft by departing employees. Which control BEST detects bulk copying of sensitive files?","options":["A longer session timeout","A welcome banner","Endpoint DLP with alerting on large sensitive-file transfers","A stronger Wi-Fi password"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Endpoint DLP with alerting on large sensitive-file transfers</strong> — Endpoint DLP that alerts on bulk transfers of sensitive files directly detects the mass-copy behavior typical of insider IP theft before or as it occurs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A longer session timeout</b>: affects idle sessions and does nothing to detect bulk file transfers.</span><span class='qd'><b>A welcome banner</b>: is a legal notice, not a detective control for data copying.</span><span class='qd'><b>A stronger Wi-Fi password</b>: protects wireless access, not internal file exfiltration.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-034","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing cryptography. Which algorithm is a SYMMETRIC block cipher widely used to encrypt data at rest?","options":["AES","ECC","Diffie-Hellman","RSA"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>AES</strong> — AES is a symmetric block cipher using a single shared key for both encryption and decryption, and is the standard choice for encrypting data at rest efficiently.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ECC</b>: is asymmetric (public-key), used for key exchange and signatures, not a symmetric block cipher.</span><span class='qd'><b>Diffie-Hellman</b>: is a key-exchange protocol, not a symmetric bulk-encryption cipher.</span><span class='qd'><b>RSA</b>: is an asymmetric algorithm using key pairs, typically for key exchange and signatures, not bulk data-at-rest encryption.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-035","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm a message's integrity without concern for confidentiality. Which cryptographic function is MOST appropriate?","options":["A symmetric cipher","A cryptographic hash function","A stream cipher","A one-time pad"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A cryptographic hash function</strong> — A cryptographic hash produces a fixed-length digest that changes if the data changes, allowing verification of integrity independently of any confidentiality goal.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A symmetric cipher</b>: provides confidentiality, not a direct integrity check of the message.</span><span class='qd'><b>A stream cipher</b>: encrypts for confidentiality and does not by itself verify integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A one-time pad</b>: is an encryption scheme for confidentiality, not an integrity verifier.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-036","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a system that uses MD5 for hashing passwords. The PRIMARY concern is that MD5:","options":["Is cryptographically broken and vulnerable to collisions","Cannot produce a fixed-length output","Requires a public/private key pair","Is too slow for modern systems"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Is cryptographically broken and vulnerable to collisions</strong> — MD5 is considered cryptographically broken; practical collision attacks undermine its integrity guarantees, so its use for security-sensitive hashing is a finding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cannot produce a fixed-length output</b>: MD5 does produce a fixed 128-bit output; that is not the issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Requires a public/private key pair</b>: MD5 is a keyless hash, not an asymmetric algorithm.</span><span class='qd'><b>Is too slow for modern systems</b>: MD5 is actually fast — speed is not the weakness, and fast hashes are poor for passwords for a different reason.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-037","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing key management. The MOST critical control for a symmetric encryption scheme is:","options":["Publishing the key on the intranet","Secure generation, distribution, storage, and rotation of keys","Using the same key indefinitely","Emailing keys to all users"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Secure generation, distribution, storage, and rotation of keys</strong> — With symmetric encryption the shared key is the crown jewel; secure key generation, distribution, storage, and periodic rotation prevent compromise that would expose all protected data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Publishing the key on the intranet</b>: exposes the secret key to anyone, destroying confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Using the same key indefinitely</b>: increases exposure over time and prevents recovery from a compromise.</span><span class='qd'><b>Emailing keys to all users</b>: transmits secrets insecurely and to unnecessary parties.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-038","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is verifying nonrepudiation for electronic transactions. Which mechanism BEST provides it?","options":["A hashed password","A network firewall","A shared symmetric key","A digital signature created with the sender's private key"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A digital signature created with the sender's private key</strong> — A digital signature made with the sender's private key can be verified with the corresponding public key, binding the message to the sender and providing nonrepudiation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A hashed password</b>: authenticates access but does not bind a specific transaction to a signer.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network firewall</b>: filters traffic and has no role in proving message origin.</span><span class='qd'><b>A shared symmetric key</b>: is known by more than one party, so it cannot uniquely bind an action to one sender.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-039","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews how data is protected while moving across the network. Which control protects data IN TRANSIT?","options":["File-level compression","RAID mirroring","Full-disk encryption","Transport Layer Security (TLS)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Transport Layer Security (TLS)</strong> — TLS encrypts data as it travels across the network between endpoints, protecting confidentiality and integrity of information in transit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>File-level compression</b>: reduces size but provides no encryption protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>RAID mirroring</b>: provides storage redundancy, not transit confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: protects data at rest on a stored device, not data moving over the network.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-040","domain":5,"obj":"5A6","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor compares symmetric and asymmetric encryption. The PRIMARY advantage of asymmetric encryption is that it:","options":["Is faster for large data volumes","Solves the key-distribution problem using public/private key pairs","Uses a single shared secret","Requires no keys at all"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Solves the key-distribution problem using public/private key pairs</strong> — Asymmetric encryption lets parties share a public key openly while keeping the private key secret, eliminating the need to pre-share a secret and solving symmetric key distribution.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Is faster for large data volumes</b>: asymmetric is actually slower; symmetric is preferred for bulk encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Uses a single shared secret</b>: that describes symmetric, not asymmetric, cryptography.</span><span class='qd'><b>Requires no keys at all</b>: asymmetric relies on key pairs; it does not eliminate keys.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-041","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a PKI. Which entity is responsible for issuing and digitally signing certificates?","options":["Relying party","Key escrow agent","Registration authority (RA)","Certificate authority (CA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Certificate authority (CA)</strong> — The CA is the trusted entity that issues and digitally signs certificates, binding a public key to a verified identity within the PKI trust model.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Relying party</b>: consumes and trusts certificates rather than issuing them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Key escrow agent</b>: holds keys in escrow for recovery, not certificate issuance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Registration authority (RA)</b>: verifies identity and forwards requests but does not itself issue/sign certificates.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-042","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor examines how a relying party checks whether a certificate has been revoked in real time. Which mechanism provides this?","options":["Key ceremony","Certificate signing request (CSR)","Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)","X.509 field extension"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)</strong> — OCSP allows a relying party to query the CA in real time for the current revocation status of a specific certificate, rather than downloading a full list.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Key ceremony</b>: is the controlled process of generating root keys, unrelated to revocation checking.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate signing request (CSR)</b>: is used to request a certificate, not to check revocation status.</span><span class='qd'><b>X.509 field extension</b>: is a certificate format element, not a revocation-checking protocol.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-043","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a PKI and finds the certificate revocation list (CRL) is updated only monthly. The PRIMARY risk is that:","options":["Certificate keys will be too short","Certificates will expire early","A compromised certificate may be trusted until the next CRL update","The CA private key will be exposed"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A compromised certificate may be trusted until the next CRL update</strong> — An infrequently updated CRL means a certificate revoked mid-cycle continues to be accepted by relying parties until the next publication, leaving a window of misplaced trust.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate keys will be too short</b>: key length is set at issuance and is unrelated to CRL timing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificates will expire early</b>: CRL frequency does not shorten certificate validity periods.</span><span class='qd'><b>The CA private key will be exposed</b>: CRL update frequency has no bearing on protecting the CA's private key.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-044","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing the MOST critical asset to protect in a PKI. Compromise of which asset would undermine trust in ALL issued certificates?","options":["A single end-user certificate","The CA's private (root) signing key","The CRL distribution point","A registration authority workstation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The CA's private (root) signing key</strong> — The CA root private key signs all certificates; if it is compromised, an attacker can forge trusted certificates, invalidating the entire hierarchy's trust.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single end-user certificate</b>: its compromise affects only that user, not the whole PKI.</span><span class='qd'><b>The CRL distribution point</b>: affects revocation availability but does not let an attacker forge trust across all certificates.</span><span class='qd'><b>A registration authority workstation</b>: is serious but scoped to enrollment integrity, not the signing of every certificate.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-045","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews certificate lifecycle management. Which stage ensures a certificate is no longer trusted before its natural expiry, e.g., after a key compromise?","options":["Issuance","Enrollment","Revocation","Renewal"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Revocation</strong> — Revocation invalidates a certificate before its scheduled expiration, and is the correct response when a private key is compromised or the certificate is no longer valid.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Issuance</b>: is the creation of the certificate, the opposite of withdrawing it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enrollment</b>: is the request/registration stage, not a mechanism to withdraw trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renewal</b>: extends validity rather than terminating trust early.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-046","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor notes the standard format used for digital certificates in most PKIs is:","options":["X.500","X.509","S/MIME","LDAP"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>X.509</strong> — X.509 is the standard defining the structure of public-key certificates used throughout PKI, specifying fields such as subject, issuer, validity, and public key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>X.500</b>: is a directory-services standard, not the certificate format itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>S/MIME</b>: is a secure email standard that uses certificates but is not the certificate format.</span><span class='qd'><b>LDAP</b>: is a directory-access protocol, not a certificate structure standard.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-047","domain":5,"obj":"5A7","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates key escrow in a PKI. The PRIMARY control concern with key escrow is:","options":["It shortens certificate validity","It speeds up certificate issuance","Escrowed private keys must be strongly protected to prevent unauthorized decryption","It removes the need for a CA"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Escrowed private keys must be strongly protected to prevent unauthorized decryption</strong> — Key escrow stores copies of private keys for recovery; if those escrowed keys are not tightly controlled, an insider could decrypt protected data, so protection of the escrow is the key concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It shortens certificate validity</b>: escrow has no effect on certificate validity periods.</span><span class='qd'><b>It speeds up certificate issuance</b>: escrow addresses recovery, not issuance speed.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for a CA</b>: escrow supplements PKI; the CA is still required to issue certificates.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-048","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing responsibilities in an IaaS deployment. The division of security duties between the cloud provider and customer is defined by the:","options":["Shared responsibility model","Business impact analysis","Data flow diagram","Service organization control report"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Shared responsibility model</strong> — The shared responsibility model delineates which security controls the provider manages versus the customer, and it shifts by service model (IaaS/PaaS/SaaS).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: assesses impact of disruptions, unrelated to cloud duty allocation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data flow diagram</b>: maps data movement but does not assign security responsibilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service organization control report</b>: is an assurance report on provider controls, not the responsibility-division framework itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-049","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews virtualization security. The compromise of which component would pose the GREATEST risk because it could affect all guest virtual machines on a host?","options":["A snapshot file","A single guest VM","The hypervisor","A virtual switch VLAN tag"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The hypervisor</strong> — The hypervisor mediates all guest VMs on a host; its compromise (a 'VM escape' or hyperjacking) could expose or control every guest, making it the highest-risk component.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A snapshot file</b>: exposes one VM's state, not control over all guests on the host.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single guest VM</b>: its compromise is typically contained to that VM, not all guests.</span><span class='qd'><b>A virtual switch VLAN tag</b>: a tagging issue is serious but narrower than full hypervisor control.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-050","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating a control that sits between users and cloud services to enforce security policy, monitor activity, and detect shadow IT. This control is a:","options":["Content delivery network","Hypervisor","Container registry","Cloud access security broker (CASB)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cloud access security broker (CASB)</strong> — A CASB brokers traffic between users and cloud services to enforce policy, provide visibility into usage (including shadow IT), and add controls like DLP and threat protection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Content delivery network</b>: caches and distributes content for performance, not policy enforcement over cloud usage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hypervisor</b>: runs virtual machines and does not broker cloud-service access policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Container registry</b>: stores container images and does not monitor cloud-service usage.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-051","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing container security. Compared with virtual machines, containers share the host operating-system kernel, which means the PRIMARY additional concern is:","options":["Inability to scale","Longer boot times","A kernel vulnerability could allow escape affecting other containers","Higher storage overhead"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A kernel vulnerability could allow escape affecting other containers</strong> — Because containers share the host kernel, a kernel-level vulnerability or misconfiguration can enable a container escape that impacts other containers, unlike more isolated VMs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Inability to scale</b>: containers scale readily; scalability is a strength, not a concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Longer boot times</b>: containers start faster than VMs, so boot time is not the concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Higher storage overhead</b>: containers are lighter-weight, reducing overhead rather than increasing it.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-052","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a SaaS contract. To obtain independent assurance over the provider's control environment, the auditor should request a:","options":["Uptime advertisement","Marketing brochure","SOC 2 Type II report","User manual"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>SOC 2 Type II report</strong> — A SOC 2 Type II report provides independent auditor assurance over the design and operating effectiveness of a provider's security controls over a period, supporting reliance decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Uptime advertisement</b>: is a marketing claim, not audited assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Marketing brochure</b>: is promotional material with no independent assurance value.</span><span class='qd'><b>User manual</b>: explains product use, not control effectiveness.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-053","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews cloud data protection. Who is ultimately accountable for the security and privacy of the organization's data placed in the cloud?","options":["The certificate authority","The cloud service provider","The customer organization (data owner)","The internet service provider"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The customer organization (data owner)</strong> — Accountability for data cannot be outsourced; even when the provider operates controls, the customer as data owner remains ultimately accountable for its protection and compliance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The certificate authority</b>: issues certificates and has no role in data ownership or accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The cloud service provider</b>: is responsible for certain controls but does not assume the customer's ultimate accountability for the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>The internet service provider</b>: provides connectivity and has no accountability for the data's security.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-054","domain":5,"obj":"5A8","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds a company stores regulated data with a cloud provider in another country. The MOST significant compliance concern the auditor should raise is:","options":["Data residency and cross-border data-transfer legal requirements","The color of the dashboard","The number of provider employees","The provider's logo design"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Data residency and cross-border data-transfer legal requirements</strong> — Storing regulated data abroad triggers data-residency and cross-border transfer laws; failing to meet these can breach privacy regulation, making it the auditor's key compliance concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the dashboard</b>: is a UI attribute with no compliance impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of provider employees</b>: is not a direct data-residency compliance concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider's logo design</b>: is cosmetic and irrelevant to compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-055","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating how a company enforces encryption and remote wipe on employee smartphones. Which technology provides these controls?","options":["Mobile device management (MDM)","A softphone application","A screen protector","A public charging station"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Mobile device management (MDM)</strong> — MDM lets the organization enforce security policies on mobile devices — encryption, passcodes, and remote wipe of lost or stolen devices — centralizing control over the fleet.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A softphone application</b>: provides voice calling and no device-security enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen protector</b>: is physical hardware unrelated to security policy enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A public charging station</b>: is a charging convenience and can itself be a risk (juice jacking), not a control.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-056","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a BYOD program. The PRIMARY control concern with allowing personal devices to access corporate data is:","options":["Corporate data on unmanaged personal devices may not be adequately protected or wiped","Employees prefer their own devices","Devices support multiple colors","Devices may have better cameras"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Corporate data on unmanaged personal devices may not be adequately protected or wiped</strong> — BYOD mixes corporate data with personal, often unmanaged devices; without containerization or MDM the organization may be unable to protect or remove its data, which is the core concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Employees prefer their own devices</b>: preference is a driver of BYOD, not a control concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Devices support multiple colors</b>: is a cosmetic attribute with no security relevance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Devices may have better cameras</b>: hardware quality is irrelevant to data-protection risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-057","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds a wireless network still uses WEP. The auditor should recommend upgrading to:","options":["MAC filtering only","A hidden SSID only","Open authentication","WPA3"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>WPA3</strong> — WEP is fundamentally broken; WPA3 provides modern, robust encryption and authentication, and is the appropriate recommendation to secure the wireless network.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>MAC filtering only</b>: is trivially bypassed via address spoofing and is not encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hidden SSID only</b>: is easily discovered and provides no real confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Open authentication</b>: provides no encryption at all, worse than WEP.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-058","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor assesses IoT devices deployed across a facility. The MOST common security weakness the auditor should test for is:","options":["Too much documentation","Overly frequent patching","Excessive battery life","Default or hardcoded credentials that are rarely changed"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Default or hardcoded credentials that are rarely changed</strong> — Many IoT devices ship with default or hardcoded credentials that are seldom changed and often cannot be, providing an easy foothold — a well-known and testable IoT weakness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Too much documentation</b>: is not a security risk and is generally beneficial.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overly frequent patching</b>: IoT typically suffers from too little patching, not too much.</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive battery life</b>: is a feature, not a security weakness.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-059","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews segmentation of IoT devices on the corporate network. The BEST practice the auditor should expect is that IoT devices are:","options":["Isolated on a separate network segment with restricted access","Given full internet and internal access","Managed with shared admin passwords","Placed on the same VLAN as finance systems"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Isolated on a separate network segment with restricted access</strong> — Segmenting IoT devices onto an isolated VLAN with restricted access limits lateral movement if a device is compromised, containing the weaker-security IoT population.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Given full internet and internal access</b>: maximizes exposure and lateral-movement risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Managed with shared admin passwords</b>: destroys accountability and eases compromise.</span><span class='qd'><b>Placed on the same VLAN as finance systems</b>: exposes sensitive systems to compromised IoT devices.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-060","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing Wi-Fi security. Which protocol provides the strongest currently available consumer wireless encryption?","options":["WEP","WPA","WPA2","WPA3"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>WPA3</strong> — WPA3 is the newest Wi-Fi security protocol, offering stronger encryption and protections (e.g., against offline dictionary attacks) than its predecessors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>WEP</b>: is obsolete and cryptographically broken.</span><span class='qd'><b>WPA</b>: is superseded and has known weaknesses (TKIP).</span><span class='qd'><b>WPA2</b>: is strong but older than and superseded by WPA3.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-061","domain":5,"obj":"5A9","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates the risk of a rogue access point on the corporate wireless network. The PRIMARY risk is that it could:","options":["Increase signal encryption","Improve wireless coverage","Allow attackers to intercept traffic or bypass network controls","Reduce electricity usage"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Allow attackers to intercept traffic or bypass network controls</strong> — A rogue AP creates an unauthorized entry point that can capture traffic or bypass perimeter controls, enabling eavesdropping and unauthorized access to the internal network.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase signal encryption</b>: a rogue AP typically weakens, not strengthens, security.</span><span class='qd'><b>Improve wireless coverage</b>: any coverage benefit is incidental and irrelevant to the security risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduce electricity usage</b>: is unrelated to the security threat posed.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-062","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating the security-awareness program. The PRIMARY objective of security awareness training is to:","options":["Change employee behavior to reduce human-related security risk","Satisfy the marketing department","Increase network bandwidth","Replace technical controls"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Change employee behavior to reduce human-related security risk</strong> — Awareness training targets the human element, aiming to change behavior so employees recognize and avoid threats like phishing, thereby reducing risk that technology alone cannot address.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Satisfy the marketing department</b>: is unrelated to the risk-reduction purpose of training.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase network bandwidth</b>: is a network-performance matter, not a training objective.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace technical controls</b>: awareness complements, not replaces, technical safeguards.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-063","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to measure the EFFECTIVENESS of anti-phishing training. The BEST metric is:","options":["Attendance at the kickoff meeting","The training budget spent","The number of training slides","The click rate on simulated phishing campaigns over time"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The click rate on simulated phishing campaigns over time</strong> — Tracking the click rate on simulated phishing tests over time shows whether behavior actually improves, providing an outcome-based measure of training effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Attendance at the kickoff meeting</b>: shows participation, not whether behavior changed.</span><span class='qd'><b>The training budget spent</b>: is an input measure, not a measure of effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of training slides</b>: measures content volume, not behavioral outcomes.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-064","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews training records and finds new hires receive security training only at their first annual all-hands. The PRIMARY concern is that:","options":["The venue is too small","Slides are outdated by default","Training is too frequent","New hires operate for months without security awareness"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>New hires operate for months without security awareness</strong> — Delaying awareness training until an annual event leaves new hires untrained during a high-risk onboarding period, so training should occur at hire, not only annually.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The venue is too small</b>: logistics are irrelevant to the awareness-gap concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Slides are outdated by default</b>: content currency is a separate issue from the timing gap identified.</span><span class='qd'><b>Training is too frequent</b>: the problem is insufficient timeliness, not excessive frequency.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-065","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor concludes that awareness training should be role-based. The BEST justification is that:","options":["Role-based training is cheaper always","It eliminates the need for policies","All employees face identical threats","Different roles face different risks and require tailored content"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Different roles face different risks and require tailored content</strong> — Risks differ by role — developers, finance staff, and executives face distinct threats — so tailoring content to role makes training relevant and more effective than a one-size-fits-all approach.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Role-based training is cheaper always</b>: cost is not the justification and is not always lower.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for policies</b>: training supports, but does not replace, policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>All employees face identical threats</b>: is false; threat exposure varies substantially by role.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-066","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates whether employees know how to report suspicious emails. The MOST important element to verify is that:","options":["The email server has a large mailbox","Reports are ignored to save time","Only managers may report","Employees know a clear, easy reporting channel exists and is used"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Employees know a clear, easy reporting channel exists and is used</strong> — A clear, easy, and used reporting channel turns aware employees into a detective control; verifying it exists and is actually used confirms the program produces actionable reporting.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The email server has a large mailbox</b>: storage size is irrelevant to reporting behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reports are ignored to save time</b>: ignoring reports defeats the purpose and increases risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only managers may report</b>: restricting reporting reduces coverage and slows detection.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-067","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor notes that awareness training addresses tailgating. Tailgating is BEST described as:","options":["Encrypting network traffic","Following an authorized person through a secure door without authenticating","Backing up data twice","Rotating encryption keys"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Following an authorized person through a secure door without authenticating</strong> — Tailgating (piggybacking) is when an unauthorized person follows an authorized one through a controlled door, bypassing physical access controls — a behavior training aims to prevent.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting network traffic</b>: is a technical confidentiality control, unrelated to physical entry.</span><span class='qd'><b>Backing up data twice</b>: concerns data availability, not physical access bypass.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rotating encryption keys</b>: is key management, not a physical-access behavior.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-068","domain":5,"obj":"5B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor observes that senior executives are exempt from phishing simulations. The auditor should note that this is a concern because executives:","options":["Are high-value targets (whaling) and their compromise carries outsized impact","Never use email","Do not have system access","Are immune to social engineering"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Are high-value targets (whaling) and their compromise carries outsized impact</strong> — Executives are prime 'whaling' targets with broad access and authority; exempting them from testing leaves the highest-impact accounts unmeasured and untrained, a notable gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Never use email</b>: is false; executives rely heavily on email.</span><span class='qd'><b>Do not have system access</b>: executives typically hold significant access and authority.</span><span class='qd'><b>Are immune to social engineering</b>: no one is immune; executives are frequently targeted.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-069","domain":5,"obj":"5B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing web-application threats. An attack that injects malicious SQL statements into an input field to manipulate a database is:","options":["Cross-site scripting","SQL injection","Denial of service","Phishing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SQL injection</strong> — SQL injection inserts crafted SQL through unsanitized input to read, modify, or destroy database data, exploiting poor input validation on the server side.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-site scripting</b>: injects client-side scripts into pages viewed by other users, not SQL into the database.</span><span class='qd'><b>Denial of service</b>: aims to exhaust resources and disrupt availability, not manipulate a database via input.</span><span class='qd'><b>Phishing</b>: is social engineering to steal credentials, not code injection into a database.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-070","domain":5,"obj":"5B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews an attack where a user's browser executes malicious script served from a trusted site, stealing session cookies. This is:","options":["Cross-site scripting (XSS)","Man-in-the-middle","Ransomware","SQL injection"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Cross-site scripting (XSS)</strong> — XSS injects malicious script that runs in victims' browsers in the context of a trusted site, enabling cookie/session theft and other client-side attacks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Man-in-the-middle</b>: intercepts communications between parties, not script execution served by the site.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ransomware</b>: encrypts data for extortion, unrelated to browser script injection.</span><span class='qd'><b>SQL injection</b>: targets the database via input, not script execution in the victim's browser.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-071","domain":5,"obj":"5B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor investigates malware that encrypts an organization's files and demands payment for the decryption key. This is:","options":["A rootkit","Ransomware","A logic bomb","Spyware"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Ransomware</strong> — Ransomware encrypts data and extorts payment for the key; the encryption-plus-ransom pattern is its defining characteristic and a major availability threat.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A rootkit</b>: hides its presence and maintains privileged access, not encrypt-for-ransom.</span><span class='qd'><b>A logic bomb</b>: triggers a malicious action on a condition, not necessarily encryption for ransom.</span><span class='qd'><b>Spyware</b>: covertly gathers information rather than encrypting files for extortion.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-072","domain":5,"obj":"5B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews an incident where an attacker intercepts and possibly alters communication between two parties who believe they are talking directly. This is a:","options":["SQL injection","Watering-hole attack","Man-in-the-middle attack","Brute-force attack"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Man-in-the-middle attack</strong> — A man-in-the-middle attacker secretly relays and may modify traffic between two parties, breaching confidentiality and integrity while both parties believe the channel is direct.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SQL injection</b>: manipulates a database via input, not intercepts communications.</span><span class='qd'><b>Watering-hole attack</b>: compromises a site the target frequents, not the interception of a live session between two parties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Brute-force attack</b>: systematically guesses credentials, not intercepting a conversation.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-073","domain":5,"obj":"5B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a coordinated attack that floods a service from many compromised hosts to exhaust its resources. This is a:","options":["Cross-site scripting","Password spraying","Distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack","Privilege escalation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack</strong> — A DDoS uses many distributed compromised systems (a botnet) to overwhelm a target's resources, denying service to legitimate users — an availability attack.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-site scripting</b>: injects scripts into web pages, not a distributed traffic flood.</span><span class='qd'><b>Password spraying</b>: tries common passwords across accounts, not a resource-exhaustion flood.</span><span class='qd'><b>Privilege escalation</b>: gains higher rights on a system, not floods a service to deny availability.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-074","domain":5,"obj":"5B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing threats. A deceptive email crafted to trick recipients into revealing credentials or clicking malicious links is:","options":["Hashing","Phishing","Sniffing","Fuzzing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Phishing</strong> — Phishing uses fraudulent messages that impersonate trusted entities to lure recipients into disclosing credentials or opening malicious content — a leading social-engineering attack.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hashing</b>: is a cryptographic integrity function, not an attack.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sniffing</b>: passively captures network traffic, not deceptive email.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fuzzing</b>: is a testing technique feeding random inputs to find bugs, not an email lure.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-075","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor distinguishes testing types. A test that identifies and reports known weaknesses without actively exploiting them is a:","options":["Vulnerability assessment","Red-team exercise","Social-engineering test","Penetration test"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Vulnerability assessment</strong> — A vulnerability assessment scans and reports known weaknesses (missing patches, misconfigurations) without exploiting them, producing a prioritized list of exposures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Red-team exercise</b>: is an adversarial, goal-based attack simulation, broader than a scan of known weaknesses.</span><span class='qd'><b>Social-engineering test</b>: targets human behavior, not a technical scan of system weaknesses.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration test</b>: actively exploits weaknesses to demonstrate impact, going beyond identification.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-076","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a penetration test. Compared with a vulnerability assessment, a penetration test PRIMARILY adds value by:","options":["Being fully automated","Avoiding any testing of controls","Listing more vulnerabilities","Actively exploiting weaknesses to demonstrate real-world impact"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Actively exploiting weaknesses to demonstrate real-world impact</strong> — A penetration test attempts to exploit vulnerabilities and chain them, demonstrating what an attacker could actually achieve and validating the real impact beyond a scan's findings.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Being fully automated</b>: pen tests rely heavily on skilled manual effort, not full automation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoiding any testing of controls</b>: pen tests deliberately test controls, the opposite of avoiding them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Listing more vulnerabilities</b>: scanning tools often list more; pen testing's value is demonstrated exploitation, not volume.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-077","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews application security testing. Which technique analyzes source code WITHOUT executing the program?","options":["Dynamic application security testing (DAST)","Static application security testing (SAST)","Fuzz testing","Load testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Static application security testing (SAST)</strong> — SAST inspects source or byte code without running it, finding flaws like injection or hardcoded secrets early in development, which is why it is called 'static' analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Dynamic application security testing (DAST)</b>: tests a running application from the outside, not static source review.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fuzz testing</b>: feeds malformed inputs to a running program, a dynamic technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load testing</b>: measures performance under load, not code-level security flaws.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-078","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating a red-team versus blue-team exercise. The red team's role is to:","options":["Defend systems and respond to alerts","Simulate adversary attacks to test defenses","Write the security policy","Approve the audit budget"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Simulate adversary attacks to test defenses</strong> — The red team emulates real attackers to probe and stress the organization's defenses, while the blue team defends — the exercise measures detection and response capability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Defend systems and respond to alerts</b>: describes the blue team, not the red team.</span><span class='qd'><b>Write the security policy</b>: is a governance activity, not the red team's attack simulation role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Approve the audit budget</b>: is a management function unrelated to red-team testing.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-079","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the scoping of a penetration test. The MOST important item to establish before testing begins is:","options":["The marketing plan","The color of the report cover","A written rules-of-engagement and authorization document","The testers' lunch schedule"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A written rules-of-engagement and authorization document</strong> — Written rules of engagement and authorization define scope, timing, methods, and legal permission, protecting both parties and ensuring the test is controlled and lawful.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The marketing plan</b>: has no bearing on penetration-test scoping or legality.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the report cover</b>: is cosmetic and irrelevant to test governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The testers' lunch schedule</b>: is logistics unrelated to authorization and scope.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-080","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a tool that scans systems and networks to identify open ports, services, and known vulnerabilities. This is a:","options":["Ticketing system","Vulnerability scanner","Word processor","Spreadsheet macro"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Vulnerability scanner</strong> — A vulnerability scanner enumerates hosts, open ports, and services and compares them against a database of known vulnerabilities to report exposures for remediation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ticketing system</b>: tracks work items and does not scan for vulnerabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Word processor</b>: creates documents and performs no scanning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Spreadsheet macro</b>: automates spreadsheet tasks, not vulnerability scanning.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-081","domain":5,"obj":"5B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing the reliability of vulnerability-scan results and finds many findings are false positives. The BEST way to improve confidence in the results is to:","options":["Ignore the scanner output entirely","Validate findings through manual verification and tuning","Increase scan frequency only","Delete the vulnerable systems"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Validate findings through manual verification and tuning</strong> — Manual validation and tuning confirm which findings are real, removing false positives so remediation effort targets genuine exposures — improving the reliability of the results.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore the scanner output entirely</b>: discards useful data and misses real vulnerabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase scan frequency only</b>: more frequent scans repeat the same false positives without validating them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete the vulnerable systems</b>: is impractical and does not address result reliability.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-082","domain":5,"obj":"5B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a platform that aggregates and correlates logs from many sources to detect and alert on security events. This is a:","options":["A spreadsheet","Security information and event management (SIEM) system","A backup appliance","A print server"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Security information and event management (SIEM) system</strong> — A SIEM centralizes log collection, normalization, and correlation across sources to detect patterns indicative of security incidents and generate alerts for analysts.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet</b>: is a manual tool, not an automated log-correlation platform.</span><span class='qd'><b>A backup appliance</b>: stores backup copies of data and does not correlate security events.</span><span class='qd'><b>A print server</b>: manages printing and has no security-monitoring function.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-083","domain":5,"obj":"5B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates log management and finds logs are collected but never reviewed. The PRIMARY concern is that:","options":["Logs are too colorful","The clock is set correctly","Storage is being wasted","Security incidents may go undetected despite available evidence"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Security incidents may go undetected despite available evidence</strong> — Unreviewed logs mean the evidence of an incident exists but no one is watching, so attacks can proceed undetected — collection without monitoring provides little protective value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Logs are too colorful</b>: is irrelevant to detection effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The clock is set correctly</b>: time sync matters but is not the core concern of unreviewed logs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storage is being wasted</b>: is a minor cost issue, not the primary security concern.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-084","domain":5,"obj":"5B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews the accuracy of event timelines across correlated logs. The control that MOST ensures logs can be reliably correlated in time is:","options":["Disabling logging on some hosts","Time synchronization via NTP across all systems","Larger log files","More colorful dashboards"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Time synchronization via NTP across all systems</strong> — Synchronizing clocks with a common time source (NTP) ensures events from different systems share a consistent timeline, which is essential for accurate correlation and investigation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling logging on some hosts</b>: removes evidence and worsens correlation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Larger log files</b>: increase retention but do not align timestamps across systems.</span><span class='qd'><b>More colorful dashboards</b>: improve presentation, not time accuracy.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-085","domain":5,"obj":"5B4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor assesses SIEM alert quality and finds analysts suffer alert fatigue from excessive alerts. The BEST remediation is to:","options":["Log nothing","Turn off the SIEM","Tune correlation rules and prioritize alerts by risk","Hire no analysts"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tune correlation rules and prioritize alerts by risk</strong> — Tuning correlation rules and risk-prioritizing alerts reduces noise so analysts focus on high-value events, addressing fatigue while preserving detection capability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Log nothing</b>: destroys the evidence base needed for monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>Turn off the SIEM</b>: eliminates detection entirely, a far worse outcome.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hire no analysts</b>: leaves alerts unhandled and detection ineffective.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-086","domain":5,"obj":"5B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews detection controls. A network sensor that monitors traffic and alerts on suspicious patterns but does not block is a(n):","options":["Intrusion prevention system (IPS)","Firewall","Load balancer","Intrusion detection system (IDS)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Intrusion detection system (IDS)</strong> — An IDS monitors traffic and raises alerts on suspicious activity but does not take blocking action, functioning as a detective rather than a preventive control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Intrusion prevention system (IPS)</b>: sits in-line and blocks traffic, whereas the described control only alerts.</span><span class='qd'><b>Firewall</b>: enforces allow/deny rules rather than alerting on suspicious patterns as its primary detective role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancer</b>: distributes traffic and provides no intrusion detection.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-087","domain":5,"obj":"5B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews continuous monitoring. The PRIMARY benefit of continuous security monitoring over periodic manual review is:","options":["It makes logs unnecessary","It eliminates the need for any controls","Timely detection of anomalies as they occur","It reduces the need for encryption"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Timely detection of anomalies as they occur</strong> — Continuous monitoring detects anomalies close to when they happen, shrinking the window between compromise and detection compared with infrequent manual reviews.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It makes logs unnecessary</b>: monitoring depends on logs; it does not remove the need for them.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for any controls</b>: monitoring supplements, not replaces, other controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>It reduces the need for encryption</b>: monitoring and encryption address different objectives.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-088","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews the incident-response plan. Which phase focuses on limiting the spread and impact of an active incident?","options":["Containment","Lessons learned","Recovery","Preparation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Containment</strong> — Containment isolates affected systems to stop the incident from spreading and causing further damage while eradication and recovery are planned, limiting overall impact.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Lessons learned</b>: is the post-incident review phase, after the incident is resolved.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery</b>: restores systems to normal after the threat is removed, not limiting active spread.</span><span class='qd'><b>Preparation</b>: establishes readiness before incidents, not limiting an active one.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-089","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates the FIRST step an organization should take when a security incident is confirmed. The BEST immediate priority is to:","options":["Contain the incident to prevent further damage","Rebuild all servers immediately","Assign blame to staff","Publicly announce the breach"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Contain the incident to prevent further damage</strong> — Once an incident is confirmed, containing it to prevent further harm is the immediate priority, preserving systems and evidence before eradication and recovery proceed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rebuild all servers immediately</b>: destroys evidence and skips containment/analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assign blame to staff</b>: is counterproductive and not an incident-handling step.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publicly announce the breach</b>: is premature before facts are known and containment is achieved.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-090","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews incident-response phases in order. Which phase comes immediately AFTER eradication?","options":["Containment","Identification","Recovery","Preparation"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Recovery</strong> — The standard sequence is preparation, identification, containment, eradication, recovery, and lessons learned; recovery follows eradication to restore systems to normal operation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Containment</b>: precedes eradication, not follows it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Identification</b>: occurs early, before containment and eradication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Preparation</b>: is the first phase, before any incident occurs.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-091","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor assesses the incident-response capability and finds no post-incident review is ever conducted. The PRIMARY consequence is that:","options":["The organization repeats the same weaknesses because lessons are not captured","Backups become unnecessary","Encryption keys expire","Incidents are contained faster"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The organization repeats the same weaknesses because lessons are not captured</strong> — Without a lessons-learned phase, root causes and control gaps are never addressed, so similar incidents recur; the review is what drives continuous improvement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Backups become unnecessary</b>: post-incident review has no bearing on backup necessity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption keys expire</b>: key lifecycles are unrelated to conducting incident reviews.</span><span class='qd'><b>Incidents are contained faster</b>: skipping reviews does not speed containment and forgoes improvement.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-092","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews incident classification. The PRIMARY reason to categorize and prioritize incidents by severity is to:","options":["Eliminate the need for a plan","Make the report longer","Allocate response resources to the most critical incidents first","Avoid documenting minor events"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Allocate response resources to the most critical incidents first</strong> — Severity-based prioritization ensures limited response resources address the highest-impact incidents first, aligning effort with business risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for a plan</b>: prioritization operates within, not instead of, the response plan.</span><span class='qd'><b>Make the report longer</b>: documentation length is not the purpose of prioritization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Avoid documenting minor events</b>: minor events should still be recorded, not skipped.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-093","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing readiness. Which incident-response phase includes developing the plan, defining roles, and training the response team?","options":["Eradication","Recovery","Identification","Preparation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Preparation</strong> — Preparation builds the capability before incidents occur — creating the plan, defining team roles, acquiring tools, and training — so responders can act effectively when needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Eradication</b>: removes the threat during an incident, not pre-incident readiness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery</b>: restores operations after eradication, not pre-incident preparation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Identification</b>: detects and confirms incidents, not the readiness-building phase.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-094","domain":5,"obj":"5B5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates when an organization should involve law enforcement in an incident. The MOST appropriate trigger is when:","options":["A password is changed","A backup completes","Any spam email is received","The incident involves criminal activity or legal reporting obligations"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The incident involves criminal activity or legal reporting obligations</strong> — Engaging law enforcement is appropriate when criminal conduct is involved or a legal/regulatory reporting duty applies, ensuring proper handling and compliance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A password is changed</b>: is a normal administrative event, not a criminal matter.</span><span class='qd'><b>A backup completes</b>: is routine operations, unrelated to law enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Any spam email is received</b>: routine spam does not warrant law-enforcement involvement.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-095","domain":5,"obj":"5B6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews forensic procedures. The documentation that tracks the seizure, custody, control, and transfer of evidence is the:","options":["Risk register","Chain of custody","Change log","Service-level agreement"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Chain of custody</strong> — The chain of custody records who handled evidence, when, and why, preserving its integrity and admissibility by demonstrating it was not tampered with.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk register</b>: catalogs risks, not evidence custody.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change log</b>: records system changes, not the handling of forensic evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service-level agreement</b>: defines service terms, unrelated to evidence handling.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-096","domain":5,"obj":"5B6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews digital-evidence collection. According to the order of volatility, which data should be collected FIRST?","options":["Data on backup tapes","Contents of RAM and running processes","Archived logs on disk","Printed documents"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Contents of RAM and running processes</strong> — The order of volatility dictates collecting the most transient data first; RAM contents and running-process data disappear on power-off, so they are captured before more persistent sources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data on backup tapes</b>: is highly persistent and can be collected later without loss.</span><span class='qd'><b>Archived logs on disk</b>: are relatively stable and less volatile than memory.</span><span class='qd'><b>Printed documents</b>: are non-volatile physical evidence, not time-critical to capture.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-097","domain":5,"obj":"5B6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor examines how investigators preserve a suspect drive. The BEST practice is to:","options":["Boot the original system normally","Analyze the original drive directly","Create a forensic bit-for-bit image and work from a verified copy","Reformat the drive first"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Create a forensic bit-for-bit image and work from a verified copy</strong> — Making a verified bit-for-bit forensic image and analyzing the copy preserves the original evidence unaltered, protecting integrity and admissibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Boot the original system normally</b>: changes disk contents and timestamps, contaminating evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Analyze the original drive directly</b>: risks altering the evidence and undermines admissibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reformat the drive first</b>: destroys the evidence entirely.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-098","domain":5,"obj":"5B6","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews how forensic examiners prove a disk image has not changed since acquisition. The BEST technique is to:","options":["Rename the image file","Store the image in the cloud","Compress the image","Compute and compare cryptographic hash values of the image before and after"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Compute and compare cryptographic hash values of the image before and after</strong> — Computing a cryptographic hash at acquisition and re-verifying it later proves the image is unchanged; matching hashes demonstrate integrity, a cornerstone of forensic reliability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rename the image file</b>: is a filename change with no bearing on content integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store the image in the cloud</b>: is a storage choice, not proof the content is unaltered.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compress the image</b>: reduces size but does not prove integrity.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-099","domain":5,"obj":"5B6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates the admissibility of digital evidence. The MOST important attribute for evidence to be admissible is that it is:","options":["Encrypted at all times","Colorful","Relevant, reliable, and lawfully obtained with an intact chain of custody","Compressed"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Relevant, reliable, and lawfully obtained with an intact chain of custody</strong> — Admissible evidence must be relevant, reliable, and legally obtained, with an unbroken chain of custody proving integrity — otherwise a court may exclude it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypted at all times</b>: encryption is not required for admissibility and could hinder examination.</span><span class='qd'><b>Colorful</b>: is irrelevant to legal admissibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressed</b>: is a storage format choice, not an admissibility criterion.</span>"},
{"id":"D5-100","domain":5,"obj":"5B6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews the role of the IS auditor in a forensic investigation. Generally, the auditor should:","options":["Ensure proper procedures are followed and involve qualified forensic specialists","Ignore evidence handling","Delete suspect files to be safe","Personally perform detailed forensic analysis without training"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Ensure proper procedures are followed and involve qualified forensic specialists</strong> — The auditor's role is to verify that sound procedures are followed and that qualified specialists handle forensics, rather than personally performing specialized analysis without competence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore evidence handling</b>: abandons the auditor's assurance responsibility over the process.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete suspect files to be safe</b>: destroys evidence and is never appropriate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Personally perform detailed forensic analysis without training</b>: exceeds the auditor's competence and can spoil evidence.</span>"}
]);
